  "text": "shows potential in clinical courses to enhance student-led learning. 46 47 48 Introduction 49 Professional degree courses require a balance of workplace learning 50 opportunities with academic elements of the curriculum (1,2). Like other [CITATION_1] undergraduate students, those studying for professional degrees have to fit their 52 study around other life commitments, which can complicate and disrupt 53 timetabling academic and workplace commitments (3-5). For example, in the UK 54 professional training of veterinary surgeons is knowledge intensive, applied and 55 focused on omni-competence (6). Historically this has led to heavy lecture 56 schedules and significant contact time with veterinary educators to enable 57 students to attain the competencies required to register as a veterinary surgeon 58 (7) . Students are also obliged to complete work experience in clinical practice, 59",
